  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Samar Boat Building</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On December 6, 2014,Typhoon Hagupit (known locally as Ruby) devastated a large portion of the Philippine island of Samar, a region that is still reeling from last year&apos;s historic Typhoon Haiyan. 
All Hands launched a response in the subsistence fishing village of Calampong on the Philippine Island of Samar within a week after the storm. During the response it became apparent that the community&apos;s biggest need for long term survival was to have the tools to feed their families -- their boats had been severely damaged and even destroyed.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Subsistence fishing communities living in poverty</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Samar boat building project is a product of our volunteers&apos; compassion and initiative to identify unmet needs and fill the gaps. So far we have worked in two villages and have built over 50 boats under the guidance of a local boat builder and shoulder-to-shoulder with the fisher men and women. Our goal is 88 boats, which will feed 402 people..

The boats are indigenous bangka paddle powered boats (12 &#x2013;16 ft), and motor boats (16-38 ft). Both use locally sourced sustainable lumber for the hull skeletons, which are then covered in a plywood shell. Both have traditional bamboo out riggers for 
stability.</narrative>
  </description>
